1e79cf11-7ed9-42ee-91cd-fdb5e7c0294b.04fdba43-f47f-4388-9a24-1875c398d593.description=
This is an operation that does nothing. It can be used for filtering flow variables by feeding them in as inputs and filtering them on the results tab.

Inputs\:
field1 - optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
field2 - optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
field3 - optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
field4 - optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Responses\:
success - this operation never fails.
1e79cf11-7ed9-42ee-91cd-fdb5e7c0294b.13c8c692-560f-47f6-b62f-402218bf53f0.description=Command-line operation. Use it for programs and scripts that you would ordinarily run from the prompt of an operating system shell. Input Parameters\: Command - the command to be run Arguments - the arguments to the command Environment - additional environment variables separated by commas, for instance XHOME\=/a/b/c,YHOME\=/x/y/z Path - additional path parameters, prepended to the parent's process path Working Dir - current working directory for the command process, it must be a valid directory. Responses\: success - if the command completes execution and its exit code is 0 failure - otherwise Result Fields\: Code - contains the exit code of the command Output String - contains the output of the command's standard output stream Error String - contains the ouptut of the command's standard error stream FailureMessage - contains the message put out by the Operations Orchestration Software system in case the command fails to complete TimedOut - contains the string 'true' if the command timed out, or 'false' otherwise Notes\: 1. An additional input named 'op_timeout' can be added in order to store a value measured in milliseconds, representing the maximum time the command is allowed to run. If this time passes without the operation reaching completion, the operation is terminated with failure by the system and the TimedOut flag is set to 'true', while the Code field will be set to -1. The system makes the best effort to destroy the subprocess (see below). 2. For the Windows operating system, the command specified by the Command input is run by the Windows command line interpreter cmd.exe as a child process of the Operations Orchestration Software system. This has the advantage that built-in commands such as dir will work; also, references to environment variables are properly expanded. However, since the child process is cmd.exe and not the process represented by the command, when a timeout happens, it is cmd.exe that gets destroyed, not the process represented by the command. 3. For the Unix family of operating systems, the command is ran directly as a child process; therefore, for more complex scenarios, it may be necessary that the command be run through a shell, e.g. /bin/sh -c " Command Arguments". Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
string1 - The first string.
string2 - The second string.
ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

responses\:
true - If the two strings are equal
false - If the two strings are not equal

1e79cf11-7ed9-42ee-91cd-fdb5e7c0294b.b703a7fe-3e03-4153-9988-574da6993ec1.description=
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable.

Returns\: 
The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable.

Responses\:
isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned.

Inputs\:

inputList\:  comma seperated list of variables to check

Reponsses\:

noNulls\:  all variables have a value

Synopsis

    This flow retrieves a list of LIFs based on either the site ID, the vServer name, or both. Optional inputs restrict the search; if none are given, all licenses are returned.
    getLifs performs the following steps\:
      1. Determine which inputs were provided (site ID, vServer name, or both).
      2. Call the remote action server (RAS) perl with the input or inputs.
      3. Compare the inputs to a list of all LIFs, compiling a list of LIFs that match the criteria of the inputs.
      4. Filter the results based on the site ID (if applicable).
      5. Pass the information to the requesting entity.

Inputs

   clusterName - The IP or host name of the NetApp cluster; specifies endpoint to run the API against (required).     
      Valid values\: Dot-decimal notation IPv4 address or RFC 1123 compliant host name.
      Default value\: None.

    vServerName - The name of the vServer used in the flow.
    siteId - The ID number of the site where the product is located.
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: None.

    overrideJRAS - Value to override the system-defined Java RAS server.
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: Hosting Eng RAS.

Results

    hpooFlowResult - The XML response specific to the functionality of the flow; in this case license information.
    flowStatus - Overall status of the flow, value is one of the string literals "success" or "failed".

Responses

    Success - All operations and subflows completed successfully.
    Failure - Some operations and/or subflows failed.

Notes
